 jurisprudence. Law thus informs Milton’s attempt to “justify the ways of God to men” and points readers toward the types of legal justice that should prevail on earth. Adding to the growing interest in the cultural history of law, The Legal Epic shows that England’s preeminent epic poem is also a sustained reflection on the role law plays in human society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aLaw and literaturezEngland. 0aLaw in literature. 0aReligion and law. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aJohn Milton.  aParadise Lost.  aRomano-canon law.  acommon law.  aearly modern England.  ajurisprudence.  ajustice.  alaw.  anatural Law.  apositivist.  areligion.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107119360 cprintz978022643513840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226435275423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226435275/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles